# relay.config — per-project relayflow config. Sourced by `flow`.
# Copy to a project's repo root as `relay.config` (committed) when auto-detection is wrong.
# If absent, `flow gates` auto-detects from the stack (package.json → npm/bun test, etc.).
# Leave a gate value EMPTY to mark it N/A (recorded as N/A, not a failure).

# ── Gates (run by `flow gates`; the Reviewer re-runs these) ──
GATE_tests="python -m pytest"
GATE_typecheck="cd frontend-react && npx tsc -b --noEmit"
GATE_build="cd frontend-react && npm run build"
GATE_lint="cd frontend-react && npm run lint"

# Two-tier gates — which gate(s) need SECRETS or NETWORK (a DB-backed suite, a build pulling private
# packages, an API key). Space-separated gate names (tests/typecheck/build/lint). A sandboxed
# cross-model Reviewer can't run these without being handed secrets (a security regression), so it
# runs `flow gates --hermetic`, which DEFERS the GATE_FULL ones (printed ⏸, not ❌, not a pass) and
# runs only the no-secrets subset — a valid Reviewer signal without secrets. Plain `flow gates` (the
# Builder / human / orchestrator, who DO have the secrets) runs everything. Empty/unset = all gates
# are hermetic (the default; nothing is deferred).
# GATE_FULL="tests build"          # e.g. tests hit a real DB and build pulls a private registry

# Run gates from a subdirectory of the repo (optional):
# GATE_CWD="frontend/app"

# Wrap a gate in setup (env, etc.) — it's eval'd as a shell command:
# GATE_build="set -a; source .env.build; set +a; bun run build"

# ── Integration ──
MAIN_BRANCH="master"
BRANCH_PREFIX="feature/"

# ── Autonomous driver (`flow drive` — OPTIONAL, opt-in) ──
# `flow drive [slug]` loops the inner relay (Builder⇄Reviewer→Done) by invoking the per-role agent
# commands until the baton reaches Done — then it STOPS and hands to the human's `flow integrate`.
# It NEVER commits to main, pushes, integrates, or deploys; the driven agents work on a feature branch.
# OPT-IN: if the command for the current owner is unset, `flow drive` refuses and runs nothing — leave
# autonomy unset to keep it off (manual `build the task` / `review the task` always work regardless).
#
# ⚠ SECURITY — the DRIVE_* commands below are NOT live settings here, and must NEVER be committed.
# They run agents UNATTENDED with guardrails OFF (claude --dangerously-skip-permissions / codex
# --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox). Committing them in a tracked relay.config hands that
# power to anyone who clones the repo — so `flow drive` REFUSES a git-tracked relay.config that defines
# DRIVE_*. Put them ONLY in an uncommitted source, in this precedence (flags > env > local file):
#   1. flags:  flow drive --builder-cmd '<cmd>' --reviewer-cmd '<cmd>'
#   2. env:    DRIVE_BUILDER_CMD=... DRIVE_REVIEWER_CMD=... flow drive
#   3. file:   relay.config.local  (gitignored; sourced after this relay.config so it wins)
# GATE_* above are safe to commit and stay here — only DRIVE_* move out of version control.
#
# Correct invocations (the commands eval'd as-is; the project owns the model + flags):
#   DRIVE_BUILDER_CMD='claude -p "build the task" --dangerously-skip-permissions'
#   DRIVE_REVIEWER_CMD='codex exec --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox "review the task"'
# Reviewer self-commit caveat: plain `codex exec -s workspace-write` can read+review, but its
# bubblewrap sandbox may block the baton commit (`bwrap: loopback`), so the Reviewer can't hand the
# baton back. Use the --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox form above (or fix bubblewrap).
# Bounded backstop — max agent invocations before `flow drive` gives up (default 6 ≈ 2 review rounds):
#   DRIVE_MAX_ITERS=6
#
# Isolation worktree location. `flow drive` runs the driven agents in a dedicated git worktree so your
# main tree/HEAD are never touched. It lives in a NORMAL directory OUTSIDE .git/ — a worktree nested in
# .git/ makes agent tools walk out to the real project root and clobber your main tree. Default base:
# ${TMPDIR:-/tmp}/relayflow-drive/<repo>-<id> (deterministic per repo+slug). Override only if needed
# (a faster tmpfs, a sandbox that forbids /tmp, etc.). It must be OUTSIDE .git/ — `flow drive` REFUSES
# a base that resolves inside the git dir (the isolation-leak path). A path inside the work tree works
# but shows up as an untracked dir; prefer somewhere outside the repo:
#   RELAY_DRIVE_DIR="/path/to/a/normal/dir"
# (If the driven agent ever escapes the worktree and touches your main tree — HEAD, branch, OR the
#  working tree/index — `flow drive` detects it and ABORTS the run: isolation is enforced, not intended.)

# ── Behind-the-scenes learning (auto-groom — OPTIONAL, opt-in) ──
# The gc-auto hook: at the END of every SUCCESSFUL `flow integrate`, if the journal has grown by
# ≥ GROOM_EVERY lines (default 25) since the last groom (.flow/groom.mark), `flow` spawns GROOM_CMD
# in the background (detached; stdout/stderr → .flow/groom.log, overwritten per run) and prints one
# notice line. The spawned session follows roles/groomer.md: it distills the journal + batons into
# a ranked improvement digest at .flow/groom-report.md, then stops. REPORT-ONLY: the groomer
# proposes; dispatching a build and integrating remain human-gated. Unset ⇒ nothing changes — no
# spawn, no mark, no report. The hook is best-effort: it never delays or fails an integrate.
#
# ⚠ SECURITY — same class as DRIVE_* above: GROOM_CMD runs an LLM UNATTENDED with guardrails off,
# and must NEVER be committed. A git-tracked relay.config that defines GROOM_CMD is refused (the
# hook spawns nothing, `flow drive` refuses to run, and `flow doctor` flags it ✗). Put it ONLY in
# an uncommitted source — the environment, or this file's gitignored sibling relay.config.local
# (sourced after relay.config; the environment wins over the local file):
#   GROOM_CMD='claude -p "groom the relay" --dangerously-skip-permissions'
#   GROOM_EVERY=25                  # journal-growth threshold (lines) before a groom spawns

# ── Runtime verification (Phase 1 — `flow verify`) ──
# The deployed/running app to exercise after Done, so review isn't only spec-deep.
# `flow verify` runs every scriptable check below (per-check ✅/❌, non-zero exit if ANY fail),
# then prints the human-only items under a "HUMAN must confirm" heading. None set → exits 0.
#
# Scriptable checks — VERIFY_SMOKE plus optional numbered VERIFY_SMOKE_1..N (each eval'd as a
# shell command; a non-zero exit = that check failed). Numbered variants are independent, so a
# gap is fine (VERIFY_SMOKE_1 + VERIFY_SMOKE_3 with no _2 still runs both).
# VERIFY_URL="https://example.com"
# VERIFY_SMOKE="curl -fsS https://example.com/api/health"        # must exit non-zero on failure
# VERIFY_SMOKE_1="curl -fsS https://example.com/api/search?q=x | grep -q results"
# VERIFY_SMOKE_2="test \"$(curl -fsS -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}' https://example.com)\" = 200"
#
# Human-only checks — VERIFY_NOTE plus optional numbered VERIFY_NOTE_1..N. No script can do these
# (a real browser click, a visual confirm); they print for the Verifier/human to action.
# VERIFY_NOTE="Manual: open VERIFY_URL, do X, expect Y."
# VERIFY_NOTE_1="Manual: log in, confirm the new filter chip appears in the sidebar."
#
# ── Browser / visual verification (Phase 1.5 — zero-dep convention) ──
# `flow` stays dependency-free: it never bundles a browser. To turn a "human must click it" NOTE
# into an automated check, the PROJECT supplies the tool and wires it as a VERIFY_SMOKE. Two ways:
#
#   1) curl + grep the RENDERED HTML (no browser at all — good for SSR/server-rendered pages):
# VERIFY_SMOKE_1="curl -fsS https://example.com/performers | grep -q 'data-testid=\"grid\"'"
#
#   2) a headless-browser script the project owns, kept under verify/ and invoked from VERIFY_SMOKE
#      (the project depends on Playwright/puppeteer — relayflow does not):
# VERIFY_SMOKE_2="node verify/homepage.mjs"     # exits non-zero if the rendered page is wrong
#      e.g. verify/homepage.mjs (project-owned, ~10 lines):
#        import { chromium } from 'playwright';
#        const b = await chromium.launch(); const p = await b.newPage();
#        await p.goto(process.env.VERIFY_URL, { waitUntil: 'networkidle' });
#        const ok = await p.locator('[data-testid="grid"]').count() > 0;
#        await b.close(); process.exit(ok ? 0 : 1);
# Keep these scripts in the project repo (committed); `flow verify` just runs them like any smoke.
